1
00:00:00,284 --> 00:00:19,204
Namo tassa bhagavato hara-hatto sambha-sambhodassam Namo tassa bhagavato hara-hatto sambha-sambhodassam

2
00:00:19,538 --> 00:00:33,715
Namo Tassa Bhagavato Arahato Sambha Sambuddhassa Homage to the Buddha, the blessed, noble and fully self-awakened one.

3
00:00:37,179 --> 00:00:46,929
So there's one or two questions here which are worth just answering because we're in the midst of meditation.

4
00:00:47,399 --> 00:00:51,146
Personally, it's our best to deal with resistance towards the practice.

5
00:00:52,569 --> 00:00:56,234
The best way is to just keep practicing.

6
00:00:58,700 --> 00:01:00,542
It's as simple as that.

7
00:01:00,603 --> 00:01:05,813
When you get that sense of not wanting to do it at any time,

8
00:01:06,096 --> 00:01:35,125
you have to be careful not to be overpowered by it not to associate with it not to identify with it so immediately you have to go into that position of there is resistance and then of course you sit and the very resistance is your object of meditation and you have to sit with it you see and everything is screaming to get up and do something else but you just stay there with it and you just wait and wait and wait until it disappears

9
00:01:35,358 --> 00:01:37,219
Now, you might not have time to do that.

10
00:01:37,920 --> 00:01:38,480
No problem.

11
00:01:38,760 --> 00:01:40,742
You have to get up and get on with daily life.

12
00:01:41,162 --> 00:01:47,688
And then you come back for your next session, your next two-hour evening session, and there's lots of resistance.

13
00:01:48,230 --> 00:01:50,772
But you say to yourself, now there's resistance.

14
00:01:50,811 --> 00:01:53,734
And you sit down and you sit with the resistance.

15
00:01:54,015 --> 00:01:55,335
Feel it, feel it, you see.

16
00:01:58,399 --> 00:02:03,102
And of course, when the resistance goes, you see, if you can stay to the very end of it,

17
00:02:03,927 --> 00:02:08,752
the very end of the resistance, it disappears, it's gone.

18
00:02:09,293 --> 00:02:15,060
And then suddenly arises the opposite, the desire to do the meditation.

19
00:02:16,161 --> 00:02:31,538
I remember on one occasion when I came back from Burma, and to my surprise, when I was really going for it, but I remember coming back, and to my surprise, I had this tremendous resistance.

20
00:02:32,227 --> 00:02:33,188
Didn't want to sit at all.

21
00:02:34,050 --> 00:02:36,854
And that's what I did.

22
00:02:36,914 --> 00:02:40,000
I thought, well, this is just another mental state.

23
00:02:40,800 --> 00:02:42,043
And eventually it passed.

24
00:02:42,524 --> 00:02:50,776
So with all these negative mental states, it's just making them an object, not identifying with it.

25
00:02:50,796 --> 00:02:51,758
I have resistance.

26
00:02:52,599 --> 00:02:55,123
There is resistance to meditation.

27
00:02:55,805 --> 00:02:56,866
And then you just sit with it.

28
00:02:57,893 --> 00:03:03,586
If you can only handle five minutes, you've handled five minutes before you get up and run for it.

29
00:03:04,149 --> 00:03:09,902
And the more you do it, the more you are not reacting to that sense of not wanting to do something.

30
00:03:11,366 --> 00:03:14,433
And eventually, as I say, it'll pass like everything else passes.

31
00:03:17,046 --> 00:03:18,590
Why resistance should come?

32
00:03:19,592 --> 00:03:21,858
There could be a multitude of reasons.

33
00:03:21,897 --> 00:03:28,913
You might have come to a point where you've done lots of meditation and nothing's happened and you wonder what's the point.

34
00:03:30,175 --> 00:03:37,590
But there might just be a, what do they call it, a sort of transposition of aversion onto the meditation.

35
00:03:37,911 --> 00:03:43,542
Remember, aversion is these negative states, well, even good states.

36
00:03:44,163 --> 00:03:47,610
They're not attached to the object that they're presenting.

37
00:03:48,012 --> 00:04:12,837
they are themselves an attitude that's locked into the heart so we have you might say a balloon of aversion and it can get averse to anything at any time for whatever reason it wants and it might just be that as aversion comes up it just grabs hold of meditation it becomes an averse state so the object of aversion the object of fear

38
00:04:13,206 --> 00:04:39,045
is a metaphor it's a symbol for you might say the actual attitudinal the attitude that's caught up inside us once you've sussed that out then of course it's not so easy to get caught up in it if you think that the meditation is making you resistant then of course you wouldn't meditate

39
00:04:40,408 --> 00:04:49,557
If you thought the meditation itself was creating the sense of aversion, then of course you'd have to stop it because you'd say to yourself, well this is no good, it's making me feel averse.

40
00:04:50,786 --> 00:04:59,516
But if you recognize that it's the aversion that's come up first, looking for an object to be averse to, then you don't blame the meditation.

41
00:04:59,737 --> 00:05:00,658
You blame the aversion.

42
00:05:00,937 --> 00:05:04,122
Of course, we're not in the blame game, but even so.

43
00:05:05,423 --> 00:05:11,290
And then you sort of sit with it, and to your surprise, to my surprise, it sort of completely disappears.

44
00:05:12,130 --> 00:05:13,932
Now that doesn't mean to say that it never comes back.

45
00:05:14,012 --> 00:05:16,634
No, it comes back, but this time you're not fooled by it.

46
00:05:16,656 --> 00:05:18,937
You just know there is aversion.

47
00:05:19,728 --> 00:05:29,281
It's just one, it's just part, it's just part of the course really, aversion to the practice.

48
00:05:35,404 --> 00:05:39,968
What would it mean for one's practice if one believes in reincarnation?

49
00:05:40,949 --> 00:05:41,589
Would it be different?

50
00:05:44,293 --> 00:05:47,435
Reincarnation, or as Buddhism would have it, rebirth.

51
00:05:48,516 --> 00:05:52,120
Rebirth stresses the fact that it's not the same person who's being reincarnated.

52
00:05:52,720 --> 00:05:54,242
So you see that even in this life.

53
00:05:54,302 --> 00:05:57,343
You're not the same as you were when you were three years old.

54
00:05:58,204 --> 00:06:03,689
So there's been a rebirthing throughout this life until we've come to this sorry state, you see.

55
00:06:04,312 --> 00:06:06,855
So, does it make a difference?

56
00:06:06,896 --> 00:06:13,665
Well, it makes a difference in this sense that it would suggest some sort of moral justice.

57
00:06:16,790 --> 00:06:23,779
If you thought that this was the only life that you had and you could get away with it, then why not?

58
00:06:24,360 --> 00:06:27,564
Because there would be no further consequence.

59
00:06:29,367 --> 00:06:33,694
Now, what happens to us from the outside

60
00:06:34,449 --> 00:07:00,795
very rarely is the direct consequence of an action because when you do something in the world it reverberates doesn't it it goes out into that matrix and when it comes back to you it comes back to you through a person or indeed through nature

61
00:07:01,855 --> 00:07:14,093
So, for instance, if you're foolish enough to stand under a tree when there's thunder and lightning and you happen to be blown up by a thunderbolt, that isn't because

62
00:07:14,966 --> 00:07:20,031
In the past life, you electrocuted people to death.

63
00:07:20,593 --> 00:07:24,656
It's because you happen to be stupid to stand under a tree.

64
00:07:26,038 --> 00:07:28,721
So there's some sort of mismatch there.

65
00:07:28,740 --> 00:07:30,701
You think, well, I was only stupid.

66
00:07:30,783 --> 00:07:32,244
I didn't expect to be blown to bits.

67
00:07:34,146 --> 00:07:41,413
So you never know the consequence of an action because you're entering into a matrix of relationships.

68
00:07:42,641 --> 00:07:43,663
So it is with people.

69
00:07:44,182 --> 00:07:49,408
You might say something which is just mildly, mildly making fun of somebody.

70
00:07:50,108 --> 00:07:52,911
A mild, a mild little sarcastic quip.

71
00:07:53,232 --> 00:08:03,701
But the other person's mortally wounded, you know, and goes about trying to destroy your life in order to regain their sense of self-respect.

72
00:08:04,603 --> 00:08:10,168
So there's no justice on that level that I can personally see.

73
00:08:10,283 --> 00:08:20,740
And even in a future life, you see, if something were to happen in a future life, again, you're into a matrix, you're into a fulsome relationship with the world around you.

74
00:08:23,985 --> 00:08:25,507
And a lot of it we just have to accept.

75
00:08:25,827 --> 00:08:31,396
You're born here into this society and this is the consequence.

76
00:08:32,474 --> 00:08:58,717
however internally something else is going on because internally is the way that you are experiencing yourself all the time and you're experiencing yourself physically and emotionally and mentally right your thoughts etc now when we do something it doesn't matter whether it's an act of speech or whatever it goes into this internal matrix

77
00:08:59,322 --> 00:09:19,726
and again you don't know the effect of it because of say a person's past history where they have a store of shame I'm thinking of a particular case and I can't remember the name a store of shame within the person

78
00:09:21,006 --> 00:09:25,957
And it's all been suppressed, it's all been repressed, it's all been down there, completely unaware of it.

79
00:09:26,639 --> 00:09:35,597
And then something happens where they lose face in close company or whatever, publicly, and they can't handle it.

80
00:09:35,879 --> 00:09:37,182
And they commit suicide.

81
00:09:38,445 --> 00:09:40,990
So you don't know the effect of an action.

82
00:09:41,543 --> 00:09:51,595
But in the general, we can say that when we do something which is beneficial, morally good, etc., it has a beneficial good effect.

83
00:09:52,395 --> 00:09:56,561
And if it's the opposite, it'll have sorry effects.

84
00:09:58,703 --> 00:10:01,707
But at some point, there has to be some resolution.

85
00:10:03,549 --> 00:10:06,874
And you can't do it in one lifetime, it seems.

86
00:10:07,355 --> 00:10:08,235
You can't do it in one.

87
00:10:08,255 --> 00:10:09,356
There's so much...

88
00:10:10,230 --> 00:10:13,659
So much gunge that you just can't get rid of it in one lifetime.

89
00:10:14,783 --> 00:10:23,025
Even the Buddha is said to have lived many lifetimes in order to build up these qualities that would allow him to come into this life.

90
00:10:23,567 --> 00:10:24,831
And when he came into the life,

91
00:10:25,232 --> 00:10:27,254
he wouldn't have been completely pure.

92
00:10:27,955 --> 00:10:29,135
Mara was still after him.

93
00:10:29,197 --> 00:10:31,418
He still had all sorts of naughty thoughts.

94
00:10:31,979 --> 00:10:40,066
And then it was only through the process of purification that he was able to put an end to all those wrong desires.

95
00:10:42,769 --> 00:10:53,197
So, from a point of view of this moral justice, there has to be some sort of resolution.

96
00:10:54,022 --> 00:11:23,673
and what the rebirth process suggests is that as you become aware of the suffering you're causing yourself and the catalyst that you are to other people's suffering remember we don't cause other people to suffer internally we can make them suffer externally you can physically hurt somebody but the reaction that's going on in the person

97
00:11:23,907 --> 00:11:26,630
is always their own specific property.

98
00:11:28,332 --> 00:11:45,797
Now that becomes obvious in Buddhist understanding because if you, if somebody else causes the suffering in me then obviously my full liberation from suffering will only happen when I've got rid of you.

99
00:11:46,047 --> 00:12:01,602
So once you recognize that that isn't what the Buddha's teaching, because he himself was fully liberated, and people continued to upset him, whether he was upset or not, but definitely did things that weren't pleasant.

100
00:12:02,624 --> 00:12:10,490
They shouted at him, they called him all sorts of names, and one of his own disciples tried to kill him, if we're to believe it, Devadatta.

101
00:12:11,451 --> 00:12:16,037
He set the elephant on him and rolled a boulder down, which hurt his big toe, it seems.

102
00:12:17,889 --> 00:12:46,597
so there has to be some sort of resolution and that takes time and that's the process of rebirth so every time you are reborn from day to day from moment to moment you carry this baggage you carry this stuff from the past that you've created and through the meditation through right understanding etc you begin to work at it undermining it

103
00:12:47,354 --> 00:12:53,363
not piling more on, or at least not piling so much on, that it undoes the work you did yesterday.

104
00:12:54,825 --> 00:12:57,008
I mean, that's normally the path that we're on.

105
00:12:57,808 --> 00:13:02,394
We clear a bit, we clear a lot, and then we dump a little bit back on.

106
00:13:03,116 --> 00:13:05,320
So it goes up and down.

107
00:13:06,181 --> 00:13:11,168
But eventually, hopefully, we can see a sort of upward movement towards betterment.

108
00:13:11,620 --> 00:13:22,465
So, there's a sort of moral justice in the sense that when we do harm, we do harm to ourselves.

109
00:13:22,946 --> 00:13:26,914
We can just do harm to ourselves and we can heal it.

110
00:13:27,075 --> 00:13:30,101
We can heal it over a long period of time.

111
00:13:32,477 --> 00:13:39,808
Now it also makes sense from the point of view of the Buddha within.

112
00:13:40,409 --> 00:13:44,054
So it also connects with the whole idea of transcendence.

113
00:13:45,076 --> 00:13:50,804
Now something in us is not part of this psychophysical organism.

114
00:13:51,605 --> 00:13:54,590
It's something that is beyond it and yet within it.

115
00:13:55,731 --> 00:13:59,177
In it but not of it, no matter how you express it.

116
00:13:59,849 --> 00:14:03,875
And somehow, it's the one that's suffering.

117
00:14:04,817 --> 00:14:11,067
When you have something like a pain in the knee, is the knee suffering?

118
00:14:11,087 --> 00:14:12,551
No.

119
00:14:12,571 --> 00:14:14,653
Something else is suffering.

120
00:14:14,673 --> 00:14:22,486
When you have a sort of foul emotion, some anxiety that comes up, the anxiety isn't suffering.

121
00:14:22,506 --> 00:14:25,231
The something that suffers the anxiety is reacting to it.

122
00:14:25,533 --> 00:14:39,255
And so there's always something other which is the one who knows, the one who's aware, the one who's in touch with, the one who feels.

123
00:14:40,298 --> 00:14:47,671
And that becomes obvious to us when we sit in meditation and we've plonked ourselves up on this observation post within ourselves.

124
00:14:47,890 --> 00:14:50,274
So everything is something that we're looking at.

125
00:14:51,014 --> 00:14:53,657
Normally speaking, your daily life, we dive in straight away.

126
00:14:53,736 --> 00:14:57,981
So if irritation comes up, you become the irritation.

127
00:14:58,001 --> 00:14:59,562
If you're depressed, I am depressed.

128
00:15:00,063 --> 00:15:08,352
But here in meditation, we're learning that there can be all this stuff going on, but somehow you've retreated your sense of self back onto this perch.

129
00:15:11,416 --> 00:15:19,485
Now, it must be this very same thing that is suffering from the delusion and has caused all this problem in the first place.

130
00:15:20,342 --> 00:15:28,456
And the whole process is for it to decide or for it to understand how it's done this and to come out of its own misery.

131
00:15:29,957 --> 00:15:33,283
It seems a bit odd, but the Buddha within is what's suffering.

132
00:15:34,664 --> 00:15:40,114
It's the one that actually is feeling and knowing and is in a state of delusion.

133
00:15:41,756 --> 00:15:43,278
As we come out of that delusion,

134
00:15:43,816 --> 00:15:52,667
obviously we're changing our relationship to this organism, this being, this human being, this human beingness.

135
00:15:54,208 --> 00:16:03,220
And in that process of changing our relationship, there's an allowing of the organism to heal itself.

136
00:16:04,841 --> 00:16:06,003
So there we are.

137
00:16:06,724 --> 00:16:08,365
We pull back into ourselves.

138
00:16:08,485 --> 00:16:12,591
We found this sacred place, you might call it, this cave.

139
00:16:13,346 --> 00:16:21,956
this hideout, and we're looking and we're feeling, and the heart feels it has permission to release its turbulences.

140
00:16:23,618 --> 00:16:39,453
And to our surprise, or at least to our benefit, we find that when the heart releases its turbulence, it's actually healing itself.

141
00:16:40,455 --> 00:16:43,118
All these inner turbulences are getting less and less and less.

142
00:16:45,089 --> 00:17:06,349
So it's only from the point of view of some sort of ethical justice that, in fact, because all this has been created out of a sense of ignorance, which was not culpable, it was an understandable mistake, you're born as this little bleating baby.

143
00:17:06,890 --> 00:17:11,755
You haven't a clue who you are and you make the big mistake of thinking that, well, this is me.

144
00:17:12,442 --> 00:17:14,185
And that's continuing throughout our lives.

145
00:17:15,087 --> 00:17:18,494
So it's a delusion for which we're not culpable.

146
00:17:18,555 --> 00:17:20,498
We're not to be blamed for it.

147
00:17:21,681 --> 00:17:32,882
And through the process of insight, this very Buddha within, this Satipaññā, becomes to recognize its own qualities.

148
00:17:34,194 --> 00:17:37,880
But by the time it gets to that, it's created this huge mess.

149
00:17:38,721 --> 00:17:42,486
So somehow the mess has to have time to liberate itself.

150
00:17:43,165 --> 00:17:47,251
The heart has to have time to liberate its problems.

151
00:17:47,271 --> 00:17:52,778
So all that obviously is going to take a bit more than one lifetime.

152
00:17:52,798 --> 00:17:58,385
So the whole idea of rebirth fits in with the idea of transcendence.

153
00:17:58,405 --> 00:17:59,667
Otherwise it doesn't make sense.

154
00:18:01,329 --> 00:18:01,569
Yeah.

155
00:18:03,490 --> 00:18:12,166
So if you don't believe any of that, or at least if you put a brake on that and say, well, no, it's all rubbish, then...

156
00:18:12,686 --> 00:18:18,234
That's fine, but then you're working for a different reason.

157
00:18:18,655 --> 00:18:23,844
You're now really just trying to get rid of the suffering within yourself.

158
00:18:24,344 --> 00:18:36,702
I'm trying to just get rid of my suffering and trying to, the best I can, over the period of time I've got, which now is quite short, is about finding an accommodation with life.

159
00:18:36,970 --> 00:18:48,565
Now that's fine, you see, but like I said this morning, this would be toning down or descaling the Buddha's teachings to a psychotherapy.

160
00:18:48,585 --> 00:18:49,546
And there's benefit in that.

161
00:18:49,786 --> 00:18:51,008
There's benefit in that.

162
00:18:51,608 --> 00:18:57,817
And it might be that when you die, you suddenly find yourself standing next to your body and you think, oh, that was a mistake.

163
00:18:58,458 --> 00:19:00,079
I'll have to...

164
00:19:02,162 --> 00:19:03,604
I'll have to get reborn.

165
00:19:04,144 --> 00:19:04,986
So...

166
00:19:06,079 --> 00:19:07,902
So that may happen and of course it may not.

167
00:19:08,682 --> 00:19:15,429
So it's for every individual really to work out their reasons for practice and to see the benefits of it.

168
00:19:15,828 --> 00:19:16,910
So the Buddha is quite clear.

169
00:19:17,170 --> 00:19:24,897
He says whether you believe in rebirth or not is immaterial because the Dharma has its benefits right here in daily practice.

170
00:19:25,818 --> 00:19:30,762
Remember in his day there were people who were also materialists.

171
00:19:31,403 --> 00:19:34,866
Didn't believe any of that stuff.

172
00:19:34,886 --> 00:19:35,968
So

173
00:19:42,749 --> 00:19:50,799
I always think it's best to put these things on a sort of back burner, really, just in case.

174
00:19:52,041 --> 00:20:01,314
Even if you were a climate change denier, it might be intelligent to behave as if there was.

175
00:20:03,877 --> 00:20:05,019
At least then you wouldn't be blamed.

176
00:20:05,298 --> 00:20:07,722
I think it was Pascal, wasn't it?

177
00:20:07,762 --> 00:20:08,844
What was it called?

178
00:20:08,884 --> 00:20:09,925
Pascal's wager.

179
00:20:10,626 --> 00:20:11,607
He said...

180
00:20:11,773 --> 00:20:18,602
Well, there may be a God and there may not, but it might be intelligent to work as if there was God, just in case.

181
00:20:19,482 --> 00:20:34,520
So it might be worth our while, even if there's not that confidence in it, to work as if there were rebirth and as if there were transcendence, that's all.

182
00:20:35,122 --> 00:20:36,262
It can't do you any harm.

183
00:20:46,451 --> 00:20:49,557
There's a little question here about mindfulness apps and stuff.

184
00:20:50,459 --> 00:20:52,041
And Headspace.

185
00:20:52,061 --> 00:20:54,366
Come on.

186
00:20:54,386 --> 00:20:55,729
They seem to be very useful.

187
00:20:56,210 --> 00:20:56,851
We're on one.

188
00:20:57,152 --> 00:21:04,345
Sadi Panya's got one on Insight Timer, which is a way for people doing this practice to connect with each other.

189
00:21:05,026 --> 00:21:08,071
I don't know, I don't quite know how it works, but

190
00:21:08,440 --> 00:21:13,066
I think you've got a list of people and it tells you how much meditation you've done.

191
00:21:13,727 --> 00:21:16,810
So you're supposed to look at it and think, he's done two hours, damn it.

192
00:21:18,732 --> 00:21:24,200
I'd better up my game here, you know.

193
00:21:24,701 --> 00:21:32,810
It's a way of people communicating because, you know, the people involved with Sadi Panya anyway live all over the place.

194
00:21:33,567 --> 00:21:44,407
The actual group that's around Satipanya itself, within travelling distance, which is about 15 miles, is very small.

195
00:21:45,250 --> 00:21:46,372
The population is very low.

196
00:21:47,354 --> 00:21:51,541
It would be a bit more substantial, I think, if I was closer to a conurbation.

197
00:21:51,521 --> 00:22:11,893
close to Birmingham or something so how how do you get that feeling of of um of being part of something you know and the support that you might get from that so for us it's insight timer seems to be one way that people I feel I think it's about 20 odd have joined it

198
00:22:12,328 --> 00:22:14,172
So feel free, inside timer.

199
00:22:16,356 --> 00:22:21,326
These other ones, I mean, I've had a quick glance at them and they seem to be all right.

200
00:22:21,405 --> 00:22:32,446
I mean, Headspace was actually created by a man who was a monk for quite a long while and then came back and wondered how he could spread it in more general ways.

201
00:22:34,537 --> 00:22:38,261
I think it brings in $100 million a year.

202
00:22:39,263 --> 00:22:43,630
So there's another very good reason for trying to create one of these.

203
00:22:47,075 --> 00:22:51,141
I'm not being cynical.

204
00:22:51,161 --> 00:22:59,432
So with all these apps, it's up to us, isn't it, to use it to our benefit, to see if it works for us.

205
00:22:59,452 --> 00:23:01,236
It's not pretty straightforward, yet.

206
00:23:09,366 --> 00:23:34,834
well it's it's it's it's asking is this the way that mindfulness etc is going to go mainstream well I don't think so because eventually people gravitate towards a teacher don't they they gravitate towards a center I mean they might use these things just to keep in contact or to create a group a virtual group

207
00:23:34,814 --> 00:23:42,009
But there has to be some basis, I think, in some real relationship, some real contact with somebody.

208
00:23:42,891 --> 00:23:44,634
At least that's how I would personally feel.

209
00:23:51,388 --> 00:23:53,733
Just going back on this business of the

210
00:23:54,810 --> 00:24:09,048
you know, believing or putting trust in reincarnation and all that, there was an occasion when I was on a train down to Brighton, and some of you might know this, and some rugby fans got on.

211
00:24:10,351 --> 00:24:15,116
And this man sat opposite me and he said, are you a Buddhist monk?

212
00:24:15,917 --> 00:24:18,240
I said, a little bit tipsy.

213
00:24:18,902 --> 00:24:19,623
I said, yes, I am.

214
00:24:20,483 --> 00:24:23,146
He said, well, I don't believe in reincarnation.

215
00:24:24,932 --> 00:24:31,082
I said, no, I said, do you know by your personal experience whether there is life after death or not?

216
00:24:32,303 --> 00:24:33,003
And he said, no.

217
00:24:33,704 --> 00:24:35,907
I said, well, why come to a conclusion?

218
00:24:37,089 --> 00:24:40,074
And his mate said, yeah, why come to a conclusion?

219
00:24:42,958 --> 00:24:45,982
Classic conversation.

220
00:24:46,002 --> 00:24:46,442
I loved it.

221
00:24:48,846 --> 00:24:54,855
I don't know whether he opened the possibility of it, but it was an interesting little conversation.

222
00:24:57,011 --> 00:25:00,938
So the rest of it we can answer more of the weekend.

223
00:25:00,958 --> 00:25:09,352
So there's one here about Stream entry, you know, how skillful is it to strive for it?

224
00:25:11,855 --> 00:25:23,796
Well When the Mahadeva actually started teaching He seems to have had very good results and

225
00:25:26,375 --> 00:25:34,012
Even the teenagers were especially open to this sort of practice and were seemingly very successful.

226
00:25:35,616 --> 00:25:44,838
Now we're going back to the 50s, you know, where there wasn't the internet and life was very simple, very pure you might say.

227
00:25:45,410 --> 00:25:58,106
And the Burmese society then, as perhaps not so much recently, was very religious, I mean incredibly religious, as you might think of, say, the Christian medieval ages.

228
00:25:58,788 --> 00:25:59,628
It was very religious.

229
00:26:00,250 --> 00:26:06,999
So the whole atmosphere of the society was about practice, about doing the practice.

230
00:26:07,019 --> 00:26:12,665
And when he began teaching in the 50s, yeah, yeah,

231
00:26:12,645 --> 00:26:16,212
They started the centre in 48, 49 or something.

232
00:26:18,636 --> 00:26:21,522
There was a lot of success and he used to give out certificates.

233
00:26:25,349 --> 00:26:28,797
There's a book on this, by the way, The History of the Mahasi Centre.

234
00:26:29,718 --> 00:26:34,366
And it says in the book, I mean, I'm paraphrasing, that those people...

235
00:26:34,769 --> 00:26:51,227
who had these certificates of course, they didn't actually stick them on their chests but they would wander around with that sort of superior air of someone who had achieved stream entry and would look down upon these poor meditators sweating away on the floor.

236
00:26:52,027 --> 00:26:53,888
So I think he stopped that.

237
00:26:56,071 --> 00:27:01,096
They don't do that anymore because of the enormous conceit that can arise.

238
00:27:02,545 --> 00:27:13,159
Normally speaking, things like, in the monastic life anyway, things like stream entrance and all that sort of stuff is really kept quite between you and the teacher.

239
00:27:14,019 --> 00:27:18,625
The teacher may tell another teacher, but it's never something that's bandied about.

240
00:27:19,507 --> 00:27:24,614
You wouldn't get, a monk or a nun will tell you what they aren't.

241
00:27:25,134 --> 00:27:26,375
They're pretty safe that way.

242
00:27:27,587 --> 00:27:29,851
But they never, they won't disclose it.

243
00:27:30,692 --> 00:27:32,494
And I think there's two reasons for it.

244
00:27:33,576 --> 00:27:50,321
You've got to be slightly careful according to the monastic rule that you don't say what you're not if there's some ulterior motive, such as getting good support, you know, finding a fan.

245
00:27:51,532 --> 00:27:55,577
So that would be a very serious mistake.

246
00:27:55,617 --> 00:27:59,702
And in fact, although you don't have to say it, there's no big confession, there's nothing.

247
00:28:00,203 --> 00:28:03,448
But in your heart of hearts, you'd know that you'd actually lost your road.

248
00:28:04,128 --> 00:28:07,553
You're no longer in communion, as it's put.

249
00:28:07,573 --> 00:28:12,680
So there's always this tremendous wariness about talking about what you've achieved.

250
00:28:14,080 --> 00:28:17,285
And as I say, it's usually between you and the teacher.

251
00:28:17,665 --> 00:28:20,088
And in lay people...

252
00:28:20,338 --> 00:28:25,105
That would be the same if you were working with a monastic teacher.

253
00:28:26,105 --> 00:28:29,631
They won't even tell you sometimes.

254
00:28:29,871 --> 00:28:31,492
They won't even tell you whether you have or not.

255
00:28:32,034 --> 00:28:37,220
And this is on the understanding that if you have made a deep insight, you'll continue.

256
00:28:37,519 --> 00:28:42,807
I mean, that's the whole point of something like stream entry, that now the Dharma gates are open.

257
00:28:43,086 --> 00:28:45,250
You've got to advance because...

258
00:28:45,314 --> 00:29:13,683
you've seen the end of the path even if it's only a flash there's something in you now which knows which way to go again in the monastic life you're not supposed to be alone in the forests in the jungles until you've achieved that for the danger is of going mad for heaven's sake but these days it's become a sort of common thing to talk about there's a whole website where people

259
00:29:13,933 --> 00:29:19,520
talk about their relationship, about their experiences and what they've attained, etc.

260
00:29:20,321 --> 00:29:31,696
And there's a sort of danger there of overestimation and of achieving something that they have thought about, that they've imaged.

261
00:29:32,478 --> 00:29:36,644
And this is the big problem with knowing too much about it.

262
00:29:37,244 --> 00:29:38,405
It's alright if you know

263
00:29:38,757 --> 00:30:06,772
lot about it but the thing is to in a sense forget it because whatever a spiritual insight is it's not within our power it's not within our willpower to attain it in fact that very willpower of trying to get this spiritual insight is going to be the biggest of all barriers and uh this definitely happened with people whom i was involved with in in those early days with my own teacher

264
00:30:07,866 --> 00:30:21,960
I remember him at the end of a retreat going through all these Vipassana insights and then telling us to decide where we were, which is absolutely, for a Western, that's mortal danger.

265
00:30:24,682 --> 00:30:33,670
Either they underestimate themselves, which is good, and they keep working, or they completely overestimate themselves and they stop working.

266
00:30:33,690 --> 00:30:37,653
And if they find that they're not moving so much, they become very discouraged.

267
00:30:38,089 --> 00:30:48,002
And I often think back, I often think of all those people that I used to meditate with in those early days in the middle, early 80s.

268
00:30:48,943 --> 00:30:52,228
I don't think I've ever seen them again.

269
00:30:52,448 --> 00:30:53,388
They've all fled.

270
00:30:55,112 --> 00:30:59,457
I only know, there's only one person that I remember whom I...

271
00:30:59,655 --> 00:31:14,526
occasionally meet up with from those days so I don't know maybe they maybe they've carried on maybe not but you can imagine if you set yourself a task and you take six months off a year some people taking six months off a year

272
00:31:15,349 --> 00:31:21,036
And just going to, say, Japan to teach English, to get a bit of money, and then coming back and do six months.

273
00:31:21,316 --> 00:31:24,199
And you do that year in, year out for five, six, seven years.

274
00:31:24,898 --> 00:31:31,266
And you're still in the same place you were seven years ago.

275
00:31:31,705 --> 00:31:34,128
So there's a sort of blowout.

276
00:31:34,148 --> 00:31:40,615
There's a sort of complete lack of, there's a destruction of confidence and you just give up.

277
00:31:42,349 --> 00:31:55,232
So these four stages of insight are to be taken as a path which we will all eventually make.

278
00:31:55,973 --> 00:31:58,699
And you can be a universalist at some point.

279
00:31:58,838 --> 00:32:02,306
Everybody has to go through it because everybody has this Buddha within.

280
00:32:02,726 --> 00:32:06,432
And this Buddha within in everybody is seeking liberation from suffering.

281
00:32:06,615 --> 00:32:25,771
but the paths leading to it are quite varied this particular format only arises in the commentaries there's nothing about this sort of stuff in any detail in the scriptures

282
00:32:26,308 --> 00:32:39,422
At the end of the discourse on how to establish right awareness, the Buddha says, well, you know, if you do this properly, you know, even within seven years, you can be fully liberated or become a non-returner.

283
00:32:39,961 --> 00:32:42,224
And then he says, no, my seven years is seven months.

284
00:32:42,944 --> 00:32:44,707
And he says, no, my seven months is seven weeks.

285
00:32:45,166 --> 00:32:51,493
He said, if you do this really properly, even within seven days, you can be fully liberated or become a non-returner.

286
00:32:52,114 --> 00:32:55,017
Now you might think, oh, seven days, that's all right, I'll do a retreat.

287
00:32:57,493 --> 00:33:09,951
but he's talking about seven days where you don't lose your mindfulness oh that's a different kettle of fish altogether and it's got to be right awareness you can't just wonder about being aware right

288
00:33:11,077 --> 00:33:20,192
So there's an inbuilt understanding that progress towards liberation is there within the system.

289
00:33:20,894 --> 00:33:31,872
But this stratifying of it in little vipassana jhanas only comes up in the commentary, in the Visuddhimagga, the path of purification.

290
00:33:31,852 --> 00:33:34,775
It's in an earlier book, too, called The Path of Purity.

291
00:33:35,355 --> 00:33:41,780
Now, that suggests to me that, you see, all that was passed from teacher to student, teacher to student.

292
00:33:41,800 --> 00:33:49,107
It wasn't something that you sort of spread out on the internet, you know, and created all sorts of ideas in people's minds.

293
00:33:49,689 --> 00:33:59,917
So, having said that, just to give you the scope of it for those people especially who don't know about this...

294
00:34:00,286 --> 00:34:12,760
When one begins to meditate, you have to put some time away to develop the necessary concentration, the necessary stillness of mind and mindfulness.

295
00:34:13,440 --> 00:34:15,764
And when you do that, of course, you get the benefits.

296
00:34:16,565 --> 00:34:21,349
And they're called the defilements of vipassana.

297
00:34:22,592 --> 00:34:30,039
You can suddenly feel tremendously peaceful, so peaceful that you've never felt before that you think, oh, this is nibbana.

298
00:34:31,048 --> 00:34:35,273
suddenly you can become tremendously insightful in the Dharma and want to write a book.

299
00:34:36,516 --> 00:34:39,420
Because you sort of understood everything.

300
00:34:40,121 --> 00:34:40,681
I mean, I had...

301
00:34:41,722 --> 00:34:43,143
He wasn't a student of mine.

302
00:34:43,585 --> 00:34:45,246
He used to come to Vihara.

303
00:34:45,427 --> 00:34:52,175
And he came back from a retreat at Amaravati and he said that he'd experienced Nibbani, you see.

304
00:34:52,396 --> 00:34:54,699
So I said to him, what happened?

305
00:34:54,719 --> 00:34:57,882
He said, well, I was sitting on the toilet and

306
00:34:59,516 --> 00:35:02,300
And this amazing mental state came.

307
00:35:02,320 --> 00:35:03,601
I was completely blissed out.

308
00:35:04,362 --> 00:35:07,306
And I said, oh, I said, but you were blissed out.

309
00:35:07,527 --> 00:35:09,349
There was a you and there was being blissed out.

310
00:35:09,389 --> 00:35:11,592
I said, well, that's not Nibbana, is it?

311
00:35:12,793 --> 00:35:15,476
And no, he said, no, no, that's Nibbana.

312
00:35:15,556 --> 00:35:17,659
He was absolutely convinced it was Nibbana, you see.

313
00:35:20,443 --> 00:35:25,710
He thought that in letting go of stuff...

314
00:35:26,601 --> 00:35:28,605
He was letting go of everything else.

315
00:35:29,465 --> 00:35:35,376
And this came, this blissed-out state, which he then presumed was Nibali, because that's what it says.

316
00:35:35,755 --> 00:35:38,641
It says the bliss of Nibali, you see.

317
00:35:38,661 --> 00:35:46,092
So you can see, it's very easy to get things wrong and to overestimate because of the words, the descriptions that are used.

318
00:35:47,454 --> 00:35:50,179
But one isn't caught up in that at all.

319
00:35:50,817 --> 00:35:53,420
And then one has an insight into impermanence.

320
00:35:53,581 --> 00:35:55,264
This is the classical way.

321
00:35:55,925 --> 00:36:04,818
Now that impermanence shakes a person because it sinks deep at some level that of their own personal impermanence.

322
00:36:04,918 --> 00:36:07,983
So it's like coming to face to face with death.

323
00:36:08,943 --> 00:36:20,300
And then there becomes what's known as these dukkha jnanas, the insights which are really to do with an emotional adjustment to that sort of insight.

324
00:36:21,141 --> 00:36:29,047
So the fear, the depression, very much like the things that you go through when you're told you've got only so much to live.

325
00:36:29,648 --> 00:36:32,458
It's the same sort of experience.

326
00:36:32,478 --> 00:36:34,324
But you keep going and then there's a...

327
00:36:35,197 --> 00:36:46,695
another insight which, as it were, tells you the gate that you're going to go through, whether it's through the gate of impermanence, or the gate of suffering, or the gate of not-self.

328
00:36:47,416 --> 00:36:51,661
And you keep going, and one day, it pops, you see, and then you made it.

329
00:36:53,644 --> 00:37:00,835
And it takes, this popping, this sort of, this process can take years.

330
00:37:01,320 --> 00:37:08,490
I met one man, he'd been working with it, and he said it took him five years to get through this.

331
00:37:08,510 --> 00:37:17,682
And what's always mysterious to me is that some people really are totally devoted to it, spend lots of time meditating.

332
00:37:18,184 --> 00:37:26,034
And apparently, from the outside, you can't understand why, but they're living a very moral, ethical life.

333
00:37:26,434 --> 00:37:29,860
They're devoting so much time to meditation, but nothing ever happens.

334
00:37:31,021 --> 00:37:37,090
So people are extremely particular and peculiar in their own little ways.

335
00:37:37,690 --> 00:37:48,088
So there's no way that you can write down this thing on a wall and say, right, I'll do this and then this will happen and this, because it just doesn't seem to work that way.

336
00:37:48,108 --> 00:37:57,282
But one of the consequences of the stream entrant is that the view of self

337
00:37:58,460 --> 00:37:59,248
is broken.

338
00:37:59,733 --> 00:38:01,855
And that's not the same as the sense of self.

339
00:38:02,577 --> 00:38:10,108
And that's why often a person who has such an insight doesn't believe that it's been an insight at all because they still feel very much like an ego.

340
00:38:10,588 --> 00:38:14,333
They still feel very much, you know, me, about me.

341
00:38:15,014 --> 00:38:19,121
But something has sort of cut through and undermined it.

342
00:38:19,621 --> 00:38:22,706
So there's a view of self and the sense of self.

343
00:38:22,726 --> 00:38:25,851
Now that sense of self doesn't go till you're fully liberated.

344
00:38:26,431 --> 00:38:30,777
That sense of self always attaches itself to some experience you're having.

345
00:38:30,757 --> 00:38:35,003
And that attachment doesn't go until the very end of the process.

346
00:38:35,043 --> 00:38:39,750
So it's not as though we're going to get rid of that sense of self very quickly.

347
00:38:40,271 --> 00:38:45,597
And the other thing is that you're clear about the practice.

348
00:38:45,617 --> 00:38:57,153
So other ideas that you had, specifically around rites and rituals, we've often given them too much power.

349
00:38:57,735 --> 00:39:00,157
So for instance, somebody...

350
00:39:00,744 --> 00:39:29,789
in Buddhism might think that what's really important is to light candles and to keep saying I take refuge in the Buddha I take refuge in the Dharma and by saying that somehow that's going to create liberation from suffering so what happens is you begin to see rituals as something that supports you don't have to get rid of them but you disempower them they're no longer really going to help you very much to liberate yourself from suffering

351
00:39:31,626 --> 00:39:39,755
And of course, the third one is that there's enough insight for a person to lose any doubt in the Buddha's teachings.

352
00:39:40,476 --> 00:39:41,556
So this opens the gate.

353
00:39:41,836 --> 00:39:44,840
This opens the gate much more to further practice.

354
00:39:44,860 --> 00:39:47,923
So you're not held back by, you know, is this right for me?

355
00:39:48,423 --> 00:39:49,666
Is this teacher any good?

356
00:39:50,326 --> 00:39:51,567
Should I be doing this anyway?

357
00:39:52,547 --> 00:39:53,108
All that's gone.

358
00:39:53,449 --> 00:40:00,856
Which doesn't mean to say that you might not change your teacher or find something else or become a Muslim, but at least the way's open, right?

359
00:40:02,288 --> 00:40:09,119
As we carry on, there's further insight into one of those three characteristics.

360
00:40:09,139 --> 00:40:09,800
It's always the same.

361
00:40:10,563 --> 00:40:11,844
Impermanence, not self.

362
00:40:12,505 --> 00:40:14,630
How we create suffering, the role of desire.

363
00:40:14,650 --> 00:40:16,012
It's always the same stuff.

364
00:40:16,534 --> 00:40:26,271
The practice at the beginning, when you're told how to sit, how to observe and what it is you're investigating, never changes.

365
00:40:26,639 --> 00:40:28,081
See, that's the wonderful thing.

366
00:40:28,141 --> 00:40:29,583
There's nothing more to learn.

367
00:40:29,905 --> 00:40:32,309
Once you've got it, that's it.

368
00:40:32,329 --> 00:40:33,652
That will take you right to the end.

369
00:40:34,333 --> 00:40:39,222
You know, it's like somebody comes on a course and they've done the opening gambit.

370
00:40:39,262 --> 00:40:41,927
Then they come to me and say, yeah, now what's the next step?

371
00:40:42,969 --> 00:40:44,992
Well, isn't the next step, this is it.

372
00:40:45,373 --> 00:40:47,938
You keep doing the same thing over and over and over again.

373
00:40:48,914 --> 00:40:57,907
So on another insight, the only thing that really happens is a lessening of your attachment to sensual pleasure.

374
00:40:58,146 --> 00:41:01,572
And with it, of course, all those other things that run along with it.

375
00:41:02,152 --> 00:41:04,376
So we talked about them this morning.

376
00:41:04,456 --> 00:41:05,878
Frustration, don't get what you want.

377
00:41:06,018 --> 00:41:09,943
You're much more easy with change and stuff like that.

378
00:41:09,963 --> 00:41:12,568
Depression, when you really haven't got what you want.

379
00:41:14,311 --> 00:41:15,192
Anxiety.

380
00:41:15,744 --> 00:41:25,813
a sense of loss, the boredom, all that's diminished, you see, because your relationship to seeking happiness in the sensual world has been attenuated.

381
00:41:26,534 --> 00:41:30,666
Some spice has been taken out of it.

382
00:41:31,000 --> 00:41:38,427
But it's only when you get to a non-returner that you're finished with the sensual world as a place to seek happiness.

383
00:41:38,608 --> 00:41:47,976
It doesn't mean to say that you don't enjoy happiness, you don't enjoy things, it's just that you're no longer confusing that with something that is truly worthwhile.

384
00:41:50,360 --> 00:42:00,449
And that's why it's called a non-returner, because such a being is not drawn back into this physical form or into a sensual form, because they're done with it.

385
00:42:00,751 --> 00:42:11,621
But they have usually, not always, don't have to, but usually they've developed very beautiful inner mental states that we call the absorption.

386
00:42:12,023 --> 00:42:13,644
And they become attached to those things.

387
00:42:14,306 --> 00:42:17,431
So that has to go too, you see, eventually.

388
00:42:17,451 --> 00:42:20,695
And the final ones are a sense of restlessness.

389
00:42:21,195 --> 00:42:30,909
Now, that restlessness, as I understand it, are just the remnants, the sort of what's left of all those bad habits we had.

390
00:42:30,889 --> 00:42:41,206
So there might be a touch, a little wave of anxiety or a wave of irritation, but they're no longer these huge things that we used to suffer from.

391
00:42:42,409 --> 00:42:52,746
So restlessness is a sort of blanket term for a low-level state of impurity in the heart.

392
00:42:53,349 --> 00:42:55,393
And conceit.

393
00:42:55,893 --> 00:42:57,835
So remember there are three conceits.

394
00:42:58,456 --> 00:43:04,204
I am better than, I'm worse than, which is often more comfortable, and I'm equal to.

395
00:43:04,244 --> 00:43:06,626
And the equal to often confuses us.

396
00:43:06,807 --> 00:43:15,739
But remember that when you gather around you all those people you're equal to, you'll find that they're either better than or worse than the other group.

397
00:43:15,759 --> 00:43:20,184
So it just feels a nicer conceit because you've got lots of friends.

398
00:43:20,164 --> 00:43:21,246
But it's still a conceit.

399
00:43:21,666 --> 00:43:22,688
It's still a comparison.

400
00:43:23,369 --> 00:43:24,831
So even that has to go.

401
00:43:24,851 --> 00:43:29,239
And then finally, just that whole business of ignorance.

402
00:43:29,259 --> 00:43:32,804
And he gives us some images for it.

403
00:43:32,824 --> 00:43:36,630
He says people who have a first insight, it's like a flash of lightning.

404
00:43:36,690 --> 00:43:40,496
They've seen everything, but it's so quick that it's gone, you might say.

405
00:43:40,635 --> 00:43:43,000
But they've seen it as a flash of lightning.

406
00:43:44,025 --> 00:43:50,536
And the next one sees it like a full starry night where there's light and they can see, but it's not so.

407
00:43:51,777 --> 00:43:54,442
The non-return is like a full moon, see?

408
00:43:54,461 --> 00:43:57,666
And the full moon in the east is even brighter than here.

409
00:43:57,686 --> 00:43:59,670
I mean, there's color, there's color.

410
00:44:00,530 --> 00:44:06,219
But you don't get to see things as they really are, like the midday sun, until you become an Arahant.

411
00:44:07,364 --> 00:44:13,362
Another nice image, which is not in the scripture, and I often wonder why, the use of climbing a mountain.

412
00:44:13,842 --> 00:44:16,231
And I can only presume that the Buddha never climbed a mountain.

413
00:44:17,675 --> 00:44:19,139
This was a romantic thing, wasn't it?

414
00:44:19,820 --> 00:44:20,784
Nobody climbed mountains.

415
00:44:20,804 --> 00:44:22,047
What did he climb a mountain for?

416
00:44:23,563 --> 00:44:30,514
It was only when this love of nature came that one began to climb mountains or to see them as something that had to be conquered.

417
00:44:32,115 --> 00:44:37,242
So where he lived on that plain, the Gangetic plain, there were hills.

418
00:44:37,724 --> 00:44:39,706
But I mean, the mountains, the Himalayas were there.

419
00:44:40,047 --> 00:44:46,275
In fact, his people would have sat sort of in, well, a few days distance from them.

420
00:44:46,615 --> 00:44:49,960
But it never occurred to them to climb it, I think.

421
00:44:50,141 --> 00:44:51,342
Why would you go up a mountain?

422
00:44:53,094 --> 00:44:58,061
So I don't think, my feeling is he never uses that image.

423
00:44:58,081 --> 00:45:04,329
But if you think about it, when you start off climbing a hill, what are you looking at?

424
00:45:04,349 --> 00:45:05,250
It's just a bit of grass, isn't it?

425
00:45:05,269 --> 00:45:07,233
A bit of grass, dirt in front of you.

426
00:45:07,693 --> 00:45:09,175
I mean, there's no joy in it at all.

427
00:45:09,856 --> 00:45:14,802
You're presuming that you'll get to a point where you'll turn around and have a vista, and that's going to be enjoyable.

428
00:45:15,503 --> 00:45:19,648
So off you go, and after a while you get a bit tired, and you think, well, I'll take a rest.

429
00:45:19,987 --> 00:45:22,190
And you turn around, and oh, it's just a lovely view, you see.

430
00:45:22,407 --> 00:45:27,010
Now, if you stay there too long, you tend to come back down for a cup of tea, right?

431
00:45:27,490 --> 00:45:30,353
But before you get cold, you think, well, better get up again.

432
00:45:30,594 --> 00:45:34,317
So off you go and you go a bit further and the scene gets broader.

433
00:45:35,338 --> 00:45:36,398
And so it is all the way up.

434
00:45:36,699 --> 00:45:42,423
But you never get the 360 degree view until you're right at the top.

435
00:45:42,443 --> 00:45:47,509
There's always a piece of dirt in front of you and what's on the other side of the mountain.

436
00:45:48,128 --> 00:45:52,313
So I always think that's a good image as to what we're trying to do here.

437
00:45:53,557 --> 00:46:01,070
So that whole business of the insights and all that, you can read about them.

438
00:46:01,309 --> 00:46:05,717
There's lots of stuff now on the website about them, and lots of people describing them.

439
00:46:05,737 --> 00:46:10,985
But I think there's a danger in that, because you can't help but have some idea.

440
00:46:11,467 --> 00:46:18,778
And you're sat there, and for instance, you're feeling, suddenly you're feeling all this bubbliness, and you think, oh yeah, that's the Vipassana Kilesa.

441
00:46:19,079 --> 00:46:20,882
That's the...

442
00:46:20,862 --> 00:46:25,289
And then something flashes across your mind and you say, oh, that's impermanence.

443
00:46:25,349 --> 00:46:27,572
I must be a sort of planner now.

444
00:46:28,715 --> 00:46:35,905
So if I, my general, my advice is, by all means, read about them, then forget about them.

445
00:46:35,927 --> 00:46:42,496
And I think we're on much surer ground when we are actually practicing to purify the heart.

446
00:46:42,516 --> 00:46:44,219
That will never disappoint us.

447
00:46:44,690 --> 00:46:51,721
The more that we purify the heart, the more we find life to be more beautiful, more enjoyable.

448
00:46:52,762 --> 00:46:57,990
And in fact, you could say that the Buddha equates happiness with virtue.

449
00:46:59,333 --> 00:47:05,983
I mean, in the discourse on the Mangala Sutta, the discourse on blessings, it's all about being virtuous.

450
00:47:07,106 --> 00:47:09,869
So it's not about owning things or doing this or doing that.

451
00:47:10,153 --> 00:47:22,009
So I'll just talk about looking after people, having a job which is, from your point of view, a service to society, and developing virtues.

452
00:47:22,769 --> 00:47:25,432
And this, he says, are the highest blessings.

453
00:47:25,452 --> 00:47:35,505
So if we move that way, at least we can often tell that there's been some movement within us as these defilements begin to lessen their hold on us.

454
00:47:36,367 --> 00:47:39,030
And that means that the defilement itself has lost power.

455
00:47:40,916 --> 00:47:43,240
So I always think that's a sort of better approach.

456
00:47:47,708 --> 00:47:52,876
I was going to go on to other stuff, but I think I'm... Oh, yes, I have.

457
00:47:52,896 --> 00:47:54,097
I've gone over time.

458
00:47:54,117 --> 00:47:54,557
Very good.

459
00:47:56,181 --> 00:48:00,106
So unless there are immediate questions arising from that...

460
00:48:05,420 --> 00:48:06,521
Fantastic.

461
00:48:06,541 --> 00:48:08,726
We can take a break.

462
00:48:09,407 --> 00:48:21,369
I can only hope my words have been of some assistance, that I have not created even greater confusion, and that by your practice you will be liberated from all suffering sooner rather than later.

